emitOn(Infrastructure.getDefaultWorkerPool()) — correct way to shift blocking I/O off Vert.x IO thread in a reactive SPI

## Context

A reactive SPI method returns `Uni<T>` and needs to make a blocking call (e.g. HTTP to an embedding service, JDBC, file I/O). The SPI is called from a `@ConsumeEvent` handler (Vert.x event bus) which runs on the Vert.x IO thread unless `blocking = true` is set.

## Technique

Use `.emitOn(Infrastructure.getDefaultWorkerPool())` on the `Uni` **before** the blocking operation. This shifts the execution to the Mutiny default worker pool:

```java
@Override
public Uni<AgentAssignment> select(AgentRoutingContext context, List<AgentCandidate> candidates) {
    // Classify (in-memory, fast — can stay on caller thread)
    List<ClassifiedCandidate> classified = classifier.classify(candidates, ...);

return Uni.createFrom()
        .voidItem()
        .emitOn(Infrastructure.getDefaultWorkerPool())  // shift here, before blocking work
        .map(ignored -> {
            // Everything from here runs on the worker pool
            float[] queryVector = embeddingProvider.embed(queryText);  // blocking HTTP call
            // ... build scored candidates ...
            return TrustCandidateClassifier.decide(classified, scored, capability);
        });
}
```

## Why This Is Non-Obvious

Three common but wrong alternatives:

**1. `Uni.createFrom().item(() -> blockingOperation())`**
Executes the supplier on the thread that subscribes (the IO thread). Still blocks if called from a `@ConsumeEvent` handler.

**2. `@Blocking` on the handler method**
Moves the *entire* handler to a worker thread, including all in-memory work before the SPI call. Wasteful and scatters the threading decision into the caller rather than the SPI implementation.

**3. `Uni.createFrom().emitter(em -> { em.complete(blocking()); })`**
Also executes on the subscribing thread unless `.emitOn()` is chained.

The correct model: the `Uni` pipeline is lazy. `.emitOn(workerPool)` inserts a thread-handoff at that point in the pipeline — everything downstream of it executes on the worker pool when the `Uni` is subscribed. Place it immediately before the first blocking call, after any fast in-memory preparation.

## Constraints

Requires `io.smallrye.mutiny:mutiny` and `io.smallrye.mutiny.infrastructure.Infrastructure` on the classpath (shipped with Quarkus). `Infrastructure.getDefaultWorkerPool()` is the standard Mutiny executor for blocking work — do not pass a custom executor unless you need isolation.

**See also:** [GE-20260529-b994c2](GE-20260529-b994c2.md) — Uni.createFrom().item(supplier) with emitOn(): supplier still runs on subscription thread (use runSubscriptionOn instead)

@Startup @ApplicationScoped prevents blocking @PostConstruct from running on Vert.x IO thread

# @Startup @ApplicationScoped prevents blocking @PostConstruct from running on Vert.x IO thread

## The technique

Add `@Startup` to any `@ApplicationScoped` bean whose `@PostConstruct` makes a blocking call:

```java
@Startup           // forces eager init on main thread during boot
@ApplicationScoped
public class MyClient {

@PostConstruct
    void validate() {
        // blocking: process probe, network check, file I/O, etc.
        new ProcessBuilder("claude", "--version").start().waitFor(10, TimeUnit.SECONDS);
    }
}
```

Without `@Startup`, Quarkus ARC initializes `@ApplicationScoped` beans **lazily** — on first injection. If the first injection happens from a reactive handler (inside a Vert.x event-loop callback, a REST endpoint, a CDI observer), the `@PostConstruct` runs on the Vert.x IO thread. Any blocking call there violates the non-blocking contract and either deadlocks under load or triggers a `BlockingOperationNotAllowedException`.

`@Startup` forces initialization during application boot on the main thread, before any reactive handlers are active.

## Why this is non-obvious

`@Startup` is documented as "run initialization at startup" but the docs frame it in terms of *when* (boot vs. first use), not *which thread*. The connection to IO-thread safety is not mentioned. Developers who know about `@Startup` typically use it for "I want this to run at boot time" — not as a reactive-safety mechanism.

The failure mode is intermittent: `@PostConstruct` is safe when the first injection happens from a non-reactive context (tests, CLI, HTTP request on a worker thread). It only fails when the first injection happens under reactive load — making it a production-only bug in many setups.

## Codebase pattern

Same pattern used by `PathParserConfigurator` and `MongoPreferenceIndexes` in casehub-platform. Canonical for any bean that initialises eagerly and blocks during `@PostConstruct`.

## Why non-obvious

The standard mental model for `@ApplicationScoped` is "singleton, available everywhere, initialized once." The lazy-init detail — and its thread-safety implications in a reactive runtime — is not in the CDI spec, only in Quarkus ARC internals. A developer migrating from Spring (`@Bean` methods always run on the startup thread) would have no reason to anticipate the problem.

**See also:** [GE-20260522-daca26](GE-20260522-daca26.md) — Mutiny MultiEmitter.emit() from Vert.x I/O thread silently drops SSE frames | [GE-20260505-da346d](GE-20260505-da346d.md) — @ApplicationScoped CDI beans are always-active in Quarkus

**See also:** [GE-20260605-e42cc5](GE-20260605-e42cc5.md) — @Blocking on plain @ApplicationScoped method causes Quarkus test classloader failure

**See also:** [GE-20260607-cedf69](GE-20260607-cedf69.md) — @Startup @ApplicationScoped does not auto-invoke arbitrary methods — requires @PostConstruct

**See also:** [GE-20260615-d065bf](GE-20260615-d065bf.md) — two @Startup @ApplicationScoped beans have no guaranteed initialization order

quarkus-flow task executor threads use Executors.newCachedThreadPool() — blocking is safe

## What it is

`WorkflowApplication`'s `DefaultExecutorServiceFactory` (the default executor used to run workflow tasks and task executor `apply()` calls) uses `Executors.newCachedThreadPool()`, not the Vert.x event loop. Blocking operations — including `await().indefinitely()`, `.join()`, and synchronous JDBC calls — are safe inside workflow task executors.

## Where to find it

`serverlessworkflow-impl-core` sources, `DefaultExecutorServiceFactory.java`:
```java
public ExecutorService get() {
    if (service == null) {
        service = Executors.newCachedThreadPool();
    }
    return service;
}
```

## Why it matters

Quarkus runs most reactive code on Vert.x IO threads where blocking causes `MutinyException: You called await() from a Vert.x I/O thread`. The quarkus-flow SDK uses its own independent cached thread pool, so workflow task executors (including `CallableTask.apply()` implementations and FuncDSL step lambdas) are NOT subject to this constraint. You can safely call `.join()` on a `CompletableFuture` or use blocking reactive subscriptions inside a workflow step.

## Why this is non-obvious

The quarkus-flow documentation does not mention the thread model for task executors. The conventional Quarkus assumption is that everything reactive runs on the Vert.x event loop. Without reading the SDK source, it's easy to add an unnecessary `@Blocking` annotation or avoid blocking calls that are actually safe.

**See also:** [GE-20260522-daca26](GE-20260522-daca26.md) — Mutiny MultiEmitter.emit() from Vert.x I/O thread silently drops SSE frames (contrast: quarkus-flow uses its own cached pool)

**See also:** [GE-20260616-312ba1](GE-20260616-312ba1.md) — @WithSession requires a Vert.x safe sub-context — worker pool threads fail

@ConsumeEvent(blocking=true) and @Transactional on the same method work correctly in Quarkus

## Symptom / Discovery

A `@ConsumeEvent` handler needs to call `@Transactional` services *and* start its own transaction (rather than relying on each called service to start its own). The question is whether placing both `@ConsumeEvent(blocking=true)` and `@Transactional` on the same method is supported.

## Context

Quarkus dispatches `@ConsumeEvent(blocking=true)` handlers on a worker thread pool (not the Vert.x IO thread). CDI interceptors — including the `@Transactional` interceptor — apply to `@ApplicationScoped` beans by default. When the event bus invokes the handler method via the CDI proxy, the `@Transactional` interceptor wraps the call, starting a JTA transaction before the method body and committing or rolling back when it exits.

## What works

```java
@ApplicationScoped
public class MyHandler {

@ConsumeEvent(value = "my-address", blocking = true)
    @Transactional
    public void handle(MyEvent event) {
        // All JPA/JTA operations here share one transaction.
        // If anything throws, the whole transaction rolls back.
        serviceA.create(...);  // joins this transaction (REQUIRED semantics)
        serviceB.update(...);  // joins this transaction
    }
}
```

The `@Transactional` annotation is applied by the CDI proxy when the event bus invokes the handler. Both annotations are active simultaneously.

## Why this is not in the docs

Quarkus documents `@ConsumeEvent` and `@Transactional` separately. The interaction between them on the same method — specifically that `blocking=true` is necessary for `@Transactional` to work correctly, and that combining both annotations is valid — is not explicitly documented. The CLAUDE.md convention for this codebase states: "`@ConsumeEvent` handlers that call `@Transactional` services must use `blocking=true`" but does not note that `@Transactional` on the handler itself is also supported.

## Verified behaviour

Tests using `@QuarkusTest` confirmed that a `@ConsumeEvent(blocking=true) @Transactional` handler:
- Starts a single JTA transaction for the full method body
- Rolls back all JPA writes (including multiple service calls) if any step throws
- Commits atomically when the method exits cleanly

**See also:** [GE-20260429-68ee24](GE-20260429-68ee24.md) — @ConsumeEvent handler silently deadlocks if .join() called without blocking=true

**See also:** [GE-20260529-e43076](GE-20260529-e43076.md) — await CDI fireAsync() delivery in @ConsumeEvent reactive chain

**See also:** [GE-20260604-d08c9f](GE-20260604-d08c9f.md) — @Transactional and @Tool can coexist on same method

Uni.createFrom().item(supplier) with emitOn() — supplier still runs on the subscription thread

## Context

A reactive SPI bridge wraps a blocking delegate using `Uni.createFrom().item(supplier)`. The goal is to offload the blocking call off the Vert.x IO thread. `.emitOn(Infrastructure.getDefaultWorkerPool())` is chained expecting it to shift execution.

## Symptom

Vert.x blocked-thread warning fires in production. The supplier still executes on the event loop thread despite the `emitOn` chain.

## Root Cause

`emitOn(executor)` controls where **downstream signals** (item, failure, completion) are dispatched to subscribers — not where the upstream computation runs. For `Uni.createFrom().item(supplier)`, the supplier is called during subscription, on the subscription thread. If the subscription originates on the IO thread, `emitOn` has no effect on when the supplier runs — by the time the signal reaches `emitOn`, the supplier has already executed and blocked.

The correct method is `runSubscriptionOn(executor)`, which routes the subscription request itself to the given executor — meaning the supplier in `item()` evaluates on that executor.

## Fix

```java
// ❌ Wrong — emitOn does not offload the item() supplier
return Uni.createFrom()
    .item(() -> delegate.render(descriptor, context))
    .emitOn(Infrastructure.getDefaultWorkerPool());

// ✅ Correct — runSubscriptionOn routes the subscription (and the supplier) to the worker pool
return Uni.createFrom()
    .item(() -> delegate.render(descriptor, context))
    .runSubscriptionOn(Infrastructure.getDefaultWorkerPool());
```

The `runSubscriptionOn` fix applies to any `Uni.createFrom().item(supplier)` wrapping a blocking call. `emitOn` is correct when the blocking work is in a downstream operator that follows it (e.g. `.voidItem().emitOn(pool).map(ignored -> blockingWork())`).

## Why This Is Non-Obvious

`emitOn` and `runSubscriptionOn` look symmetrical — both redirect to an executor — but they operate at different points in the Mutiny pipeline. The Vert.x blocked-thread warning is the only signal something is wrong; there is no compile-time error. The existing technique GE-20260529-ff186e shows `emitOn` working correctly for a different pattern; this gotcha explains when it silently fails.

### Why this fix

`runSubscriptionOn` is the right semantic: "evaluate this on the worker pool", which is exactly what's needed for a bridge that wraps a blocking operation in a supplier. `emitOn` is the right semantic for "deliver results to consumers on this executor" — a different concern.

## Constraints

Applies to `Uni.createFrom().item(supplier)` and `Uni.createFrom().item(value)`. For `Uni.createFrom().emitter(...)` or operator chains, `emitOn` placed before the blocking operator is correct.

## Update — CDI request-scoped beans unavailable inside the item() supplier

Because `Uni.createFrom().item(supplier)` executes the supplier at subscription time (on the
subscription thread), any CDI `@RequestScoped` bean accessed inside the lambda will throw
`ContextNotActiveException` if the subscription happens on a non-request thread (e.g. a Vert.x
worker thread or Quarkus managed executor).

**Common case:** `CurrentPrincipal` is `@RequestScoped`. Injecting it into an
`@ApplicationScoped` reactive service and reading it inside the Uni lambda is safe only
if the subscription always originates on a request thread. If the caller schedules
the Uni on a worker thread (e.g. via `@Blocking` or `runSubscriptionOn`), the CDI
request scope is no longer active and the read throws.

**Fix:** Capture any `@RequestScoped` value as a local variable BEFORE the Uni is
constructed — on the calling (request) thread — then use the captured value inside
the lambda:

```java
// ❌ Wrong — reads CurrentPrincipal inside the lambda (may run off request thread)
@Inject CurrentPrincipal principal;

return Uni.createFrom().item(() -> {
    String tenancyId = principal.tenancyId();  // ContextNotActiveException if not on request thread
    return service.process(tenancyId);
});

// ✅ Correct — capture on the calling (request) thread before the Uni
String tenancyId = principal.tenancyId();  // safe: called on request thread
return Uni.createFrom().item(() -> {
    return service.process(tenancyId);       // captured local — no CDI scope dependency
});
```

This applies to any `@RequestScoped` bean: `CurrentPrincipal`, HTTP headers via
`@Context HttpHeaders`, security context, etc.

## Variant — Vert.x timer re-dispatch (nested runSubscriptionOn inside flatMap)

When a fault handler uses a Vert.x timer for backoff delay and then re-dispatches
via `flatMap(submit)`, the `submit()` method's `runSubscriptionOn` only affects the
inner subscription. The `flatMap` itself and any operations before the inner Uni
execute on the timer's callback thread — which is the Vert.x event loop.

```java
// ❌ Wrong — submit() uses runSubscriptionOn internally, but the flatMap
// chain before the inner subscription runs on the timer's event-loop thread
return Uni.createFrom().<Void>emitter(em -> {
        long timerId = vertx.setTimer(delayMs, id -> em.complete(null));
        em.onTermination(() -> vertx.cancelTimer(timerId));
    })
    .flatMap(ignored -> workerExecutionManager.submit(...));
    // submit().runSubscriptionOn protects the inner supplier,
    // but initial chain operations may run on the event loop

// ✅ Correct — emitOn(workerPool) before flatMap ensures the entire
// chain after the timer fires on the worker pool
return Uni.createFrom().<Void>emitter(em -> {
        long timerId = vertx.setTimer(delayMs, id -> em.complete(null));
        em.onTermination(() -> vertx.cancelTimer(timerId));
    })
    .emitOn(Infrastructure.getDefaultWorkerPool())
    .flatMap(ignored -> workerExecutionManager.submit(...));
```

