JPA JOINED inheritance subclass with its own repository bypasses base-class save() invariants — invisible until a constraint surfaces it

## Symptom

After adding a `UNIQUE(subject_id, sequence_number)` constraint to the base `ledger_entry` table, an `@ObservesAsync` CDI observer that persists an `ActorIdentityBindingEntry` (a `LedgerEntry` subclass) starts failing with `ConstraintViolationException: UNIQUE index violation ... VALUES (UUID, 0)`. The `sequence_number = 0` reveals the entry was persisted without sequence assignment.

## Context

`LedgerEntry` uses JPA JOINED inheritance. `JpaLedgerEntryRepository.save()` assigns `sequenceNumber` via an atomic MERGE on a sequence table. `ActorIdentityBindingEntry extends LedgerEntry` but is persisted through `JpaActorIdentityBindingRepository.save()` — a separate repository that calls `em.persist()` directly without sequence assignment. Before the UNIQUE constraint, both entries silently got `sequence_number = 0`. After the constraint, the second entry for the same subject violates uniqueness.

## Root Cause

JPA JOINED inheritance stores all subclass rows in the same base table. Any invariant enforced in the base repository's `save()` (sequence assignment, pseudonymisation, compliance sanitisation) is silently bypassed when a subclass has its own repository with a direct `em.persist()`. There is no JPA mechanism that forces all subclasses through the same save pipeline — it is a convention that must be enforced architecturally.

## Fix

Extract shared save-pipeline logic into a CDI bean that all repositories inject:

```java
@ApplicationScoped
class LedgerSequenceAllocator {
    @Inject @LedgerPersistenceUnit EntityManager em;

int nextSequenceNumber(UUID subjectId) {
        // MERGE + SELECT
    }
}

// Both repositories inject the allocator:
class JpaLedgerEntryRepository {
    @Inject LedgerSequenceAllocator sequenceAllocator;

public LedgerEntry save(LedgerEntry entry) {
        entry.sequenceNumber = sequenceAllocator.nextSequenceNumber(entry.subjectId);
        em.persist(entry);
    }
}

class JpaActorIdentityBindingRepository {
    @Inject LedgerSequenceAllocator sequenceAllocator;

public ActorIdentityBindingEntry save(ActorIdentityBindingEntry entry) {
        entry.sequenceNumber = sequenceAllocator.nextSequenceNumber(entry.subjectId);
        em.persist(entry);
    }
}
```

## Why This Is Non-Obvious

The subclass repository looks correct — it persists a valid entity. The bypass is invisible because: (1) the base table has no constraint that would surface the missing invariant; (2) `em.persist()` succeeds silently with default field values; (3) the subclass and base class are in different packages with different CDI lifecycles; (4) the problem only manifests when a DB constraint (UNIQUE, CHECK) or cryptographic verification makes the missing invariant observable. Without such a constraint, the data corruption is silent and permanent.

Quarkus service classes don't inherit Logger — each class needs its own static Logger field

### Symptom
Adding a `LOG.warn(...)` call to a service class fails to compile with "cannot find symbol: variable LOG" even though the companion reactive service has a Logger. Searching the class for `Logger` finds nothing.

### Context
In a codebase where a blocking service (`MessageService`) and its reactive mirror (`ReactiveMessageService`) coexist, developers often assume the Logger is inherited or available by convention. In the qhorus project, `ReactiveMessageService` had `private static final Logger LOG = Logger.getLogger(ReactiveMessageService.class)` at line 71. `MessageService` had none.

### Root cause
Java loggers are not inherited. Each class that needs logging must declare its own static Logger field. Quarkus provides JBoss Logging by default; there is no automatic injection or inheritance mechanism.

### Fix
Add the field at the top of the class body, before the first `@Inject`:

```java
import org.jboss.logging.Logger;

@ApplicationScoped
public class MessageService {

private static final Logger LOG = Logger.getLogger(MessageService.class);

@Inject
    ChannelService channelService;
    // ...
}
```

### Why this is non-obvious
When two sibling service classes exist — one with a Logger, one without — developers assume the one without still has access to the Logger (via CDI, inheritance, or a shared parent class). In Quarkus `@ApplicationScoped` beans there is no shared parent in scope; each CDI bean needs its own Logger declaration.

JPA JOINED inheritance: filtering by subclass column vs inherited column for same UUID — only inherited uses the index

## JPA JOINED inheritance: filtering by subclass column vs inherited column for same UUID — only inherited uses the index

### Symptom

A JPQL query using `WHERE e.caseId = :id` runs full scans on the subclass join despite an index existing for the same logical filter. Switching to `WHERE e.subjectId = :id` — where `subjectId` is set to the same UUID — makes the query use the index.

### Context

In JPA `JOINED` inheritance, the entity hierarchy maps to multiple tables joined on `id`. Consider:

```java
@Entity @Table(name = "ledger_entry")
public abstract class LedgerEntry {
    @Column(name = "subject_id") public UUID subjectId;  // indexed
    @Column(name = "sequence_number") public int sequenceNumber;
}

@Entity @Table(name = "case_ledger_entry")
public class CaseLedgerEntry extends LedgerEntry {
    @Column(name = "case_id") public UUID caseId;  // same value, NOT indexed
}
```

DB index: `CREATE INDEX idx ON ledger_entry (subject_id, sequence_number)` — on the **parent** table only.

At runtime, `caseId` and `subjectId` are always set to the same UUID. But the JPQL predicate determines which table column the WHERE clause targets:

```sql
-- WHERE e.caseId = :id → filters on case_ledger_entry.case_id (no index)
SELECT ... FROM ledger_entry l JOIN case_ledger_entry c ON l.id = c.id WHERE c.case_id = ?

-- WHERE e.subjectId = :id → filters on ledger_entry.subject_id (indexed)
SELECT ... FROM ledger_entry l JOIN case_ledger_entry c ON l.id = c.id WHERE l.subject_id = ?
```

### Fix

When the same UUID is stored in both the subclass and inherited columns, always query via the inherited field to use the index:

```java
// Correct — uses idx_ledger_entry_subject_seq:
em.createQuery(
    "SELECT e FROM CaseLedgerEntry e WHERE e.subjectId = :id ORDER BY e.sequenceNumber DESC",
    CaseLedgerEntry.class)
  .setParameter("id", caseId)
  .setMaxResults(1)
  .getResultStream().findFirst();

// Avoid — same result, no index benefit:
em.createQuery(
    "SELECT e FROM CaseLedgerEntry e WHERE e.caseId = :id ORDER BY e.sequenceNumber DESC",
    CaseLedgerEntry.class)
```

### Why this is non-obvious

Hibernate makes both fields appear semantically equivalent in the Java model — same type, same runtime value, same query results. There is no warning from Hibernate's query plan, no IDE hint, and no mention of this in the JPA or Hibernate ORM documentation for JOINED inheritance. The only way to discover it is to inspect the schema DDL and trace which table each mapped column lives on.

`final hashCode()` in parent — update the protected field from setters instead of overriding

## `final hashCode()` in parent — update the protected field from setters instead of overriding

**ID:** GE-0143
**Stack:** Java (all versions)
**Symptom:** Compile error: `hashCode() in SubClass cannot override hashCode() in ParentClass — overridden method is final`
**Context:** When implementing structural equality in a subclass where the parent class declares `hashCode()` as `final`. Common in frameworks where the base node class controls its own hash via a mutable protected field.

### What was tried (didn't work)
```java
// In BetaNode — FAILS to compile
@Override
public int hashCode() {
    int h = getClass().hashCode();
    h = 31 * h + (leftInput  != null ? leftInput.getId()  : 0);
    h = 31 * h + (rightInput != null ? rightInput.getId() : 0);
    return h;
}
```

### Root cause
Java does not allow overriding `final` methods. The standard advice ("implement hashCode in the subclass") is blocked at compile time. The error message correctly identifies the problem but gives no direction for the fix.

### Fix
If the parent exposes a `protected` field that its `final hashCode()` reads, write an `updateHashCode()` method in the subclass that computes the hash and assigns it directly to that field. Call it from every setter that affects the hash:

```java
// In BetaNode
private void updateHashCode() {
    int h = getClass().hashCode();
    h = 31 * h + (leftInput  != null ? leftInput.getId()  : 0);
    h = 31 * h + (rightInput != null ? rightInput.getId() : 0);
    this.hashcode = h;  // protected int hashcode declared in BaseNode
}

@Override
public void setLeftInput(BaseNode n) {
    super.setLeftInput(n);
    updateHashCode();
}

public void setRightInput(BaseNode n) {
    this.rightInput = n;
    updateHashCode();
}
```

### Why non-obvious
The compile error points at `hashCode()` but not at the solution. The fix requires knowing (a) the parent has a mutable protected field that the final method reads, and (b) to update it from setters rather than at compute time. Both facts require reading the parent class internals.

*Score: 12/15 · Included because: non-obvious workaround to a hard compiler wall; field-mutation approach is counterintuitive · Reservation: only applicable when parent exposes the mutable field*

Quarkus JPA subclass @Inject EntityManager omits parent qualifier — silently uses wrong PU in multi-datasource

### Symptom
`findByCaseId` and related queries return empty results or run against the wrong datasource in multi-datasource deployments. In single-datasource deployments everything works — no error, no warning.

### Context
JPA repository subclass extends a parent that injects `@LedgerPersistenceUnit EntityManager em`. The subclass adds its own EntityManager field for additional query methods. In a deployment with two datasources (e.g. engine default + qhorus), the unqualified field resolves to the default PU.

### Root cause
CDI `@Inject EntityManager` without a qualifier resolves to the **default** persistence unit. The parent's qualifier is not inherited by the subclass's own `@Inject` fields. Both EntityManagers are injected but target different PUs — the subclass silently queries the wrong one.

### Fix
Replicate the same CDI qualifier on the subclass's EntityManager field:

```java
// Before — silently uses wrong PU in multi-datasource
@Inject EntityManager caseEm;

// After — correct
@Inject @LedgerPersistenceUnit EntityManager caseEm;
```

Rule: every `@Inject EntityManager` field in a named-datasource class hierarchy must carry the named qualifier, regardless of which class in the hierarchy declares it.

### Why this is non-obvious
The parent class correctly qualifies its EntityManager and all parent queries work. The subclass compiles and works in single-datasource deployments where the unqualified injection accidentally resolves to the only available PU. The bug is invisible until a second datasource is added — at which point queries silently target the wrong PU with no error, no exception, and no logged warning.

