Default interface method as bridge consolidator — combine two-step activation checks across many implementors

## The Problem

A Phase 1 migration bridge requires each of N plugin classes to evaluate a two-step activation check in `canActivate(CaseFile)`: first check `requires()` key presence, then check `activateIf()` extra gates. Writing this inline in 8 plugins creates brittle duplication — if the combination logic changes, all 8 must be updated.

## The Technique

Add a `default` method to the interface that combines the two steps. Each plugin bridge delegates to it in a single expression:

**In the interface:**
```java
public interface TaskDefinition {
    default Set<String> requires() { return Set.of(); }
    default Predicate<CaseContext> activateIf() { return ctx -> true; }

/** Phase 1 bridge helper — mirrors Phase 2 SequenceWorker evaluation order. */
    default boolean testActivation(CaseContext ctx) {
        return requires().stream().allMatch(ctx::contains) && activateIf().test(ctx);
    }
}
```

**In each of the 8 plugin bridges:**
```java
@Override
public boolean canActivate(CaseFile caseFile) {
    return testActivation(new CaseFileContext(caseFile));
}
```

## Why Non-Obvious

The instinct is to extract a static utility method or write it inline. The `default` method approach is better here because:
1. It lives on the interface that all implementations share — no import needed
2. It encodes the Phase 2 semantics explicitly (requires first, then activateIf) in the contract, not in utility code
3. When Phase 2 arrives and bridge methods are deleted, the `default` method serves as documentation of the intended evaluation order

The technique also prevents the subtle bug where refactoring `activateIf()` to remove key re-checks (making it "extra gates only") breaks the bridge — the `testActivation()` helper re-adds the key check from `requires()`, so the bridge stays correct.

CDI container wiring vs service-loader wiring in large JVM frameworks

## Pattern

Large JVM frameworks that expose extension points make a foundational choice: wire extensions via **CDI container injection** or via **service-loader / explicit registration**. Both achieve the same structural depth (thousands of interfaces, deep abstraction hierarchies) but differ radically in how dependencies flow at runtime.

### CDI container wiring (Quarkus style)

Extensions are beans. Callers inject them via `@Inject`, `Instance<T>`, or `@Any Instance<T>`. The CDI container owns lifetime and resolution.

```java
// Extension point
public interface ExpiryPolicy {
    String name();
    boolean isExpired(Session s, Duration timeout);
}

// Discovery — zero explicit registration
@ApplicationScoped
public class PolicyRegistry {
    @Inject @Any Instance<ExpiryPolicy> policies;

public ExpiryPolicy get(String name) {
        return policies.stream()
            .filter(p -> p.name().equals(name))
            .findFirst().orElseThrow();
    }
}
```

### Service-loader wiring (Hibernate style)

Extensions are registered via `META-INF/services/<InterfaceFQN>` files or explicit `ServiceRegistry` calls. The framework owns resolution; no CDI container required.

```java
// META-INF/services/org.hibernate.integrator.spi.Integrator
// → com.example.MyIntegrator

// Discovery — explicit service lookup
ServiceLoader<Integrator> loader =
    ServiceLoader.load(Integrator.class, classLoader);
```

## Why this is non-obvious

The two approaches look structurally identical at a coarse level — same number of interfaces, same abstraction depth ratio. A structural fingerprint alone won't distinguish them. The signal is in the **injection-to-file ratio**: CDI-wired frameworks approach 0.4 injections/file; service-loader frameworks stay near 0.002. That gap (200×) survives normalisation and is the discriminator.

This matters when **integrating the two styles**: a Hibernate extension brought into a Quarkus application must be wrapped in a CDI producer or adapter bean — the wiring strategies don't compose directly.

### Alternatives considered

- **Manual factory / registry**: explicit `Map<String, Extension>` maintained in code. Works, but requires every extension author to register manually. Fragile at scale.
- **Reflection-based scanning**: scan classpath for implementations. Non-deterministic ordering, classloading hazards, slow startup.
- **Both at once (hybrid)**: use service-loader for bootstrap discovery, CDI for runtime injection. Adds complexity; only warranted when a framework must work both inside and outside a CDI container.

ChatModel.doChat(ChatRequest) is the override point for test doubles — not chat(ChatRequest)

## The technique

When implementing a test `ChatModel` without mocks (because `AiMessage`/`ChatResponse` have final methods), override `doChat(ChatRequest)` — not `chat(ChatRequest)`:

```java
ChatModel testModel = new ChatModel() {
    @Override
    public ChatResponse doChat(final ChatRequest request) {
        // inspect request, return appropriate response
        return ChatResponse.builder()
                .aiMessage(new AiMessage("{...json...}"))
                .build();
    }
};
```

`chat(ChatRequest)` is a **default method** in the `ChatModel` interface that calls `chat(ChatRequest, ChatRequestOptions)`, which then calls `doChat(ChatRequest)`. The chain applies listeners, merges request parameters, and fires `onRequest`/`onResponse` hooks. By overriding `doChat()`, the test skips the listener chain and returns directly.

`casehub-engine-api`'s `Agent.execute()` calls `model.chat(request)` which eventually reaches `doChat()`.

## Why this is non-obvious

`chat(ChatRequest)` and `chat(ChatRequest, ChatRequestOptions)` are the visible API methods that developers see in IDE autocompletion. `doChat(ChatRequest)` is buried as an implementation detail — a `default` method with a `throw new RuntimeException("Not implemented")` body that exists specifically as the override target. The JavaDoc doesn't prominently surface this as the intended extension point for test doubles.

**See also:** [GE-20260618-5008f5](../casehub-engine/GE-20260618-5008f5.md) — @Alternative @Priority(10) CDI test bean avoids Quarkus CDI restart (related CDI testing technique)

casehub-engine in-memory: CaseCompleted CDI event unreliable in @QuarkusTest — GoalReached fires first and is more reliable

When a case completes via goal satisfaction in tests using `casehub-engine-persistence-memory`, `CaseLifecycleEvent(eventType="CaseCompleted")` is not reliably delivered to CDI `@ObservesAsync` observers. The case DOES reach `CaseStatus.COMPLETED` (visible via `caseInstanceRepository.findByUuid().getState()`), making this especially misleading — the repository poll works, but the CDI event never arrives within the test assertion window.

### Symptom

`await().atMost(3, SECONDS).untilAsserted(() -> assertThat(ae.escalationStatus).isEqualTo(COMPLETED))` times out with `ConditionTimeoutException` even though the engine case is in `CaseStatus.COMPLETED`.

### Root cause

Two async hops separate goal satisfaction from `CaseCompleted`:

1. `GoalReachedEventHandler` fires `GoalReached` via `lifecycleEvents.fireAsync()` → chains `.evaluateCompletion()`
2. `evaluateCompletion` publishes to a Vert.x event bus address (`eventBus.publish(CASE_STATUS_CHANGED, ...)`)
3. A separate `CaseStatusChangedHandler` fires `CaseCompleted` via `lifecycleEvents.fireAsync()`

Steps 2–3 are a Vert.x event bus hop on top of the first `fireAsync`. In tests with a single-threaded Vert.x event loop and in-memory stores, the second CDI event either doesn't fire or arrives after the test assertion window closes.

`GoalReached` fires at Step 1 — before the second hop — and is reliably delivered to `@ObservesAsync` observers in tests.

### Fix

Accept both `"GoalReached"` and `"CaseCompleted"` event types in observers. Since `GoalReached` fires once per goal (not once per case completion), add an idempotency guard on the write-back. Extract the write to a dedicated `@ApplicationScoped` bean with `@Transactional(REQUIRES_NEW)` so it commits atomically and can be mocked in unit tests:

```java
// Observer — accept both event types
if (!"GoalReached".equals(event.eventType()) && !"CaseCompleted".equals(event.eventType())) return;
// ...resolve aeId...
statusUpdater.markCompleted(aeId); // idempotent — returns false if already COMPLETED
```

```java
@ApplicationScoped
public class AeStatusUpdater {

@Transactional(TxType.REQUIRES_NEW)
    public boolean markCompleted(UUID aeId) {
        AdverseEvent ae = AdverseEvent.findById(aeId);
        if (ae == null || ae.escalationStatus == AeEscalationStatus.COMPLETED) return false;
        ae.escalationStatus = AeEscalationStatus.COMPLETED;
        return true;
    }
}
```

`REQUIRES_NEW` ensures the status write commits even if the outer observer transaction rolls back (e.g. ledger write failure).

### Alternatives considered

- `CaseCompleted`-only filter: observer never fires in `@QuarkusTest` with in-memory engine. Await always times out.
- Inline `AdverseEvent.findById()` in the listener: works in integration tests but makes the listener untestable with plain Mockito (Panache static calls require Quarkus container). Extracting to a CDI bean solves both the mockability and the `REQUIRES_NEW` isolation.

### Why this is non-obvious

The case genuinely reaches `CaseStatus.COMPLETED` — you can see it via `caseInstanceRepository.findByUuid().getState()`. The symptom looks like a timing race on the status update, not a missing CDI event. And in production with a full Vert.x cluster, `CaseCompleted` fires correctly — so the gap is specific to the test's in-memory engine setup.

@RequestScoped CDI bean silently fails in Quarkus @ConsumeEvent handlers — no error, no WorkItem

### Symptom
Integration test expects a WorkItem to be created after firing a case event. The assertion sees an empty store — `Expected size: 1 but was: 0`. No error, no exception, no log warning.

### Context
A `@ConsumeEvent(blocking = true)` handler calls `WorkItemService.create()`, which transitively injects `TenantScopedPrincipal` — a `@RequestScoped` bean. The handler runs on a Quarkus worker thread where no request context is active. CDI proxy throws `ContextNotActiveException` internally, but the event bus swallows it — the handler appears to complete normally.

The `@RequestScoped` bean wins CDI resolution over a `@DefaultBean @ApplicationScoped` alternative because non-default beans have higher priority. So the broken bean is always selected.

### What was tried (didn't work)
- Checking event bus wiring (correct — other handlers on the same bus work)
- Verifying WorkItemStore contents (empty — the create call never completes)
- Adding `@ActivateRequestContext` to the test method (doesn't help — handler runs on a different thread)

### Root cause
`@ConsumeEvent` handlers — even with `blocking = true` — do not activate a CDI request context. Any `@RequestScoped` bean in the injection chain throws `ContextNotActiveException`. The Vert.x event bus catches the exception and does not propagate it to the caller (fire-and-forget semantics).

### Fix
Exclude the `@RequestScoped` bean from the test CDI context and provide an `@ApplicationScoped` replacement:

```properties
# application.properties
quarkus.arc.exclude-types=io.casehub.work.runtime.service.TenantScopedPrincipal
```

```java
@ApplicationScoped
public class NoOpCurrentPrincipal implements CurrentPrincipal {
    @Override public String actorId() { return "system"; }
    @Override public Set<String> groups() { return Set.of(); }
    @Override public String tenancyId() { return TenancyConstants.DEFAULT_TENANT_ID; }
    @Override public boolean isCrossTenantAdmin() { return false; }
}
```

### Why this is non-obvious
The failure is completely silent. No exception in logs, no test error beyond the assertion. The `@RequestScoped` bean wins CDI resolution automatically (higher priority than `@DefaultBean`), so you never suspect it's the problem. You debug the event bus, the handler logic, and the store — all correct. The request scope issue only surfaces when you trace the full injection chain.

casehub-qhorus MessageService methods using Panache static calls bypass InMemory store in @QuarkusTest

## Symptom

In a `@QuarkusTest` that relies on `InMemoryMessageStore` (from `casehub-qhorus-testing`), calling `messageService.findAllByCorrelationId(correlationId)` returns an empty list even though messages were dispatched to that correlationId moments before in the same test. The messages exist in the InMemory store but are invisible to this method.

## Context

`OversightGateService.fulfill()` calls `messageService.findAllByCorrelationId(gateId.toString())` to look up the original COMMAND message's Long ID (needed as `inReplyTo` for the RESPONSE dispatch). In `@QuarkusTest` with InMemory stores, this always returns empty — causing the service to log "no COMMAND message found" and fail open.

## Root Cause

`MessageService.findAllByCorrelationId()` is implemented with a Panache static call:

```java
public List<Message> findAllByCorrelationId(final String correlationId) {
    return Message.<Message> find("correlationId = ?1 ORDER BY id ASC", correlationId).list();
}
```

This bypasses the `MessageStore` interface entirely and queries Hibernate/H2 directly. The `InMemoryMessageStore` (the `@Alternative @Priority(1)` test bean) stores messages in a `ConcurrentHashMap` — it is never consulted by Panache static calls.

Most other `MessageService` methods inject and delegate to `MessageStore` — those work correctly with InMemory stores. Only the methods that use Panache static calls are affected.

## Fix

Wrap the problematic method with `@InjectSpy` in the test class and override only the bypassing method to scan the InMemory store:

```java
@InjectSpy
MessageService messageService;

@Inject
InMemoryMessageStore messageStore; // or inject the store interface directly

@BeforeEach
void mockFindAllByCorrelationId() {
    doAnswer(inv -> {
        String correlationId = inv.getArgument(0);
        return messageStore.findAll().stream()
            .filter(m -> correlationId.equals(m.correlationId))
            .sorted(Comparator.comparingLong(m -> m.id))
            .collect(Collectors.toList());
    }).when(messageService).findAllByCorrelationId(anyString());
}
```

All other `messageService` calls continue to use the real implementation; only `findAllByCorrelationId` is bridged to the InMemory store.

## Why This Is Non-Obvious

The `InMemoryMessageStore` gives the impression that all Qhorus data access is intercepted in tests. It isn't — only access that flows through the `MessageStore` interface is intercepted. Methods that call Panache directly bypass it silently: no error, just empty results. The real `InMemoryMessageStore` is injected correctly; it simply never receives the query.

**See also:** [GE-20260512-66d997](GE-20260512-66d997.md) — Panache static methods bypass CDI @Alternative stores (general pattern)

---

**Resolved in: casehub-qhorus 0.2-SNAPSHOT (2026-06-01, casehubio/qhorus#228)** — All four Panache-direct methods (`findByCorrelationId`, `findAllByCorrelationId`, `findResponseByCorrelationId`, `findDoneByCorrelationId`) now route through `messageStore.scan()`. `MessageQuery` gained `correlationId(String)` and `messageType(MessageType)` include filters; `MessageQueryJpql` and `InMemoryMessageStore.scan()` both apply them. The `@InjectSpy` workaround is no longer needed on fixed versions. The `invalidation_triggers` field predicted this fix exactly.

### Alternative — Mock MessageService + direct fanOut (ChannelBackend testing)

**Approach:** When testing a `ChannelBackend` implementation that calls `MessageService` read methods, mock `MessageService` entirely with `@InjectMock` and trigger the backend via `gateway.fanOut()` directly instead of going through `MessageService.dispatch()`.

**When to use:** Testing the `post()` logic of a `ChannelBackend` in isolation — verifying it calls the LLM, dispatches the right `MessageType`, and sets the correct `inReplyTo`. Does not test the full dispatch pipeline.

**Pros:** Avoids the store-seam issue entirely; tests the backend in isolation; fast (no full Qhorus transaction overhead).
**Cons/trade-offs:** Does not prove the backend integrates correctly with the full dispatch→fanOut→commitment lifecycle.

```java
@QuarkusTest
class MyChannelBackendTest {
    @Inject ChannelGateway gateway;
    @Inject MyChannelBackendFactory factory;

@InjectMock MessageService messageService;   // mock to control findByCorrelationId
    @InjectMock MyLlmService llm;               // mock to control LLM output

@Test
    void queryDispatchesResponse() {
        UUID channelId = UUID.randomUUID();
        String correlationId = UUID.randomUUID().toString();

// Stub the inReplyTo lookup
        Message stubQuery = new Message();
        stubQuery.id = 42L;
        when(messageService.findByCorrelationId(correlationId)).thenReturn(Optional.of(stubQuery));
        when(llm.review(any(), any(), any(), any(), any()))
            .thenReturn(new ReviewResult(false, "Looks good."));

// Register the backend
        factory.put(session);
        gateway.initChannel(channelId, new ChannelRef(channelId, "my-prefix/" + sessionId));

// Trigger via fanOut — bypasses MessageService.dispatch() entirely
        gateway.fanOut(channelId, "my-prefix/" + sessionId, new OutboundMessage(
            UUID.randomUUID(), "human:user", MessageType.QUERY, "Is this clear?",
            UUID.fromString(correlationId), null, ActorType.HUMAN));

// Verify the backend dispatched a RESPONSE
        ArgumentCaptor<MessageDispatch> captor = ArgumentCaptor.forClass(MessageDispatch.class);
        verify(messageService).dispatch(captor.capture());
        assertThat(captor.getValue().type()).isEqualTo(MessageType.RESPONSE);
        assertThat(captor.getValue().inReplyTo()).isEqualTo(42L);
    }
}
```

**See also:** [GE-20260608-5087c8](GE-20260608-5087c8.md) — @QuarkusTest @InjectSpy MessageService: COMMAND with correlationId does not trigger ChannelBackend.post()

MutableCurrentPrincipal @ApplicationScoped state leaks between @QuarkusTest classes — silent empty results

### Symptom
Tests pass in isolation, fail in suite — tenant-scoped store queries return empty `Optional` or empty `List`, not errors. No CDI exception, no `NullPointerException`. The failure is completely silent.

### Context
A `MutableCurrentPrincipal` test bean (`@ApplicationScoped @Alternative @Priority(100)`) provides mutable `tenancyId` for tenancy isolation tests. Tenancy tests call `setTenancyId(TENANT_B)` and reset via `@BeforeEach` within their own class. But `@ApplicationScoped` beans survive across `@QuarkusTest` classes — after the last test method of a tenancy test class, the bean retains `TENANT_B`. Subsequent test classes expecting `DEFAULT_TENANT_ID` silently get wrong query results.

### What was tried (didn't work)
- Adding `@AfterEach` to tenancy test classes — fragile, easy to miss for new tests
- Making each non-tenancy test inject and reset the principal — doesn't scale

### Root cause
`@ApplicationScoped` CDI beans persist across `@QuarkusTest` classes within the same Quarkus test application lifecycle. JUnit test class ordering is non-deterministic. A tenancy test class that sets `tenancyId = TENANT_B` in its last test method leaves the bean in that state for all subsequent classes.

### Fix
Register a `QuarkusTestBeforeEachCallback` via ServiceLoader that resets the principal before every test method across all test classes:

```java
public class MutablePrincipalResetCallback implements QuarkusTestBeforeEachCallback {
    @Override
    public void beforeEach(QuarkusTestMethodContext context) {
        var container = Arc.container();
        if (container != null) {
            var handle = container.instance(MutableCurrentPrincipal.class);
            if (handle.isAvailable()) {
                handle.get().reset();
            }
        }
    }
}
```

Register in `META-INF/services/io.quarkus.test.junit.callback.QuarkusTestBeforeEachCallback`.

### Why this is non-obvious
The failure is silent — tenant-scoped queries filter by `tenancyId` and return empty results when the ID doesn't match. No exception is thrown. The symptoms (empty Optional, empty List) look like missing test data, not wrong tenant context. You only discover the real cause when test ordering changes or a new tenancy test class is added.

### Why this fix
A ServiceLoader callback is infrastructure-level — it fires before every test method in every `@QuarkusTest` class without requiring any per-class wiring. Individual `@BeforeEach` resets are fragile (miss one class, silently break another). The callback makes the problem structurally impossible.

### Alternatives considered
- Per-class `@BeforeEach` reset: fragile, doesn't scale
- `@RequestScoped` principal: would need request context activation in every test, breaks `@ApplicationScoped` store injection patterns
- JUnit `@Order` on test classes: masks the problem, doesn't fix it

**See also:** [GE-20260512-e552f7](GE-20260512-e552f7.md) — @ApplicationScoped bean state persists across @QuarkusTest classes | [GE-20260612-279b44](GE-20260612-279b44.md) — CDI bean ordering non-determinism causes registry key collision | [GE-20260519-12efe9](GE-20260519-12efe9.md) — QuarkusTestProfile.getEnabledAlternatives() scopes @Alternative to single test class

@ApplicationScoped bean state persists across @QuarkusTest classes — tests pass in isolation but fail in suite

## @ApplicationScoped bean state persists across @QuarkusTest classes — tests pass in isolation but fail in suite

### Symptom

Tests pass when run individually (`mvn test -Dtest=MyTestClass`) but fail with wrong counts, unexpected state, or assertion errors when the full test suite runs. The failure is non-deterministic — depends on test execution order.

### What was tried (didn't work)

- Running `@BeforeEach` cleanup in one test class — doesn't help other test classes that share the same bean
- `@QuarkusTest` `@TestProfile` isolation — still shares the same app instance within a profile

### Root cause

All `@QuarkusTest` classes in a module share a single Quarkus application instance. State accumulated in `@ApplicationScoped` beans (rate limiters, registries, caches, counters) persists between test classes. There is no automatic reset between classes.

### Fix

Three complementary strategies:

```java
// 1. Expose package-private reset hooks on stateful beans
@ApplicationScoped
public class AuthRateLimiter {
    void resetForTest() { this.state.clear(); }  // package-private
}

// 2. Call reset in @AfterEach in every test class that uses the bean
@AfterEach void cleanup() { rateLimiter.resetForTest(); }

// 3. Use unique identifiers per test to avoid cross-test interference
String name = "test-" + UUID.randomUUID();
```

### Why this is non-obvious

Developers accustomed to Spring's per-test context reset or JUnit's per-test instance lifecycle expect a clean slate for each test class. Quarkus's shared-instance model is correct for production fidelity but requires explicit cleanup discipline. The flakiness is order-dependent and hard to reproduce reliably.

