Read-modify-write on thread-safe store is not atomic — concurrent writers lose updates

### Symptom

Under concurrent writes, a list value in a thread-safe store ends up with fewer entries than expected — some updates are silently lost. The store itself is thread-safe but the caller's update is not.

### Context

Any pattern where a caller (a) reads a mutable value from a thread-safe store, (b) modifies it outside the store, then (c) writes it back. Common with lists that are stored as values in a `ConcurrentHashMap` or similar.

### What was tried (didn't work)

```java
// RACE: two threads both read the same list, modify it, write back — last write wins
public static void recordWorkerCompletion(CaseContextImpl ctx, String workerName) {
    WritablePanelImpl episodic = ctx.writablePanel(ContextPanel.EPISODIC);
    List<Map<String, Object>> workers = episodic.getList("workers", Map.class); // read (lock released)
    // ← another thread reads the same list here ←
    workers = new ArrayList<>(workers);
    // ... modify workers list ...
    episodic.set("workers", workers); // write (lock acquired) — may overwrite concurrent write
}
```

`getList()` acquires and releases the read lock. The modification runs unguarded. `set()` acquires the write lock. Between the read and write, another thread calling the same method reads the same stale list and its write overwrites the first thread's increment.

### Root cause

Thread-safety of individual operations on a store does not make sequences of those operations atomic. The entire read-modify-write sequence must execute under a single lock.

### Fix

Hold the write lock for the full read-modify-write sequence using an atomic update method:

```java
// Add to the store class:
public void engineUpdate(String key, UnaryOperator<Object> updater) {
    lock.writeLock().lock();
    try {
        Object current = data.get(key);
        Object updated = updater.apply(current);
        if (updated != null) data.put(key, updated);
        else data.remove(key);
    } finally {
        lock.writeLock().unlock();
    }
}

// Caller uses the atomic update:
episodic.engineUpdate("workers", currentValue -> {
    List<Map<String, Object>> workers = currentValue instanceof List
        ? new ArrayList<>((List<Map<String, Object>>) currentValue)
        : new ArrayList<>();
    // ... modify workers ...
    return workers;
});
```

### Why this is non-obvious

Developers typically understand that individual operations on `ConcurrentHashMap` are thread-safe and assume this extends to "I read it safely, I write it safely, so the sequence is safe." The race window is invisible in unit tests because tests run sequentially by default. The bug only appears under load — Quartz worker completion callbacks, for example, can arrive concurrently for the same case and trigger simultaneous list updates.

H2 MERGE WHEN NOT MATCHED races under concurrent transactions — synchronized + separate REQUIRES_NEW CDI bean prevents PK violation

### Symptom

`org.h2.jdbc.JdbcSQLIntegrityConstraintViolationException: Unique index or primary key violation` on a table used as a per-subject sequence counter, when two concurrent `REQUIRES_NEW` transactions both execute a MERGE upsert on the same key:

```sql
MERGE INTO ledger_subject_sequence AS t
USING (SELECT CAST(?1 AS UUID) AS sid) AS s ON t.subject_id = s.sid
WHEN MATCHED THEN UPDATE SET next_seq = t.next_seq + 1
WHEN NOT MATCHED THEN INSERT (subject_id, next_seq) VALUES (s.sid, 2)
```

The violation fires on the INSERT in the WHEN NOT MATCHED branch.

### Context

A `@ApplicationScoped @Transactional(REQUIRED)` save method (called from inside a caller's `REQUIRES_NEW` transaction) runs the MERGE to atomically increment a per-subject sequence counter. Under concurrent load, two threads both enter the MERGE simultaneously — both evaluate WHEN NOT MATCHED before either commits — both attempt INSERT of the same primary key.

PostgreSQL serializes this correctly: the first MERGE acquires an exclusive row lock on the target; the second blocks until the first commits. H2 does not provide this row-level serialization for the NOT MATCHED branch.

### Root cause

H2's `MERGE INTO ... WHEN NOT MATCHED THEN INSERT` is not serialized under concurrent transactions for new keys. Two concurrent transactions can both evaluate the WHEN NOT MATCHED predicate as true (neither can see the other's uncommitted INSERT), and both proceed to INSERT the same primary key — causing a constraint violation.

PostgreSQL's MERGE acquires a row-level lock before INSERT, preventing the concurrent evaluation. H2 does not.

### Fix

**Atomically commit the sequence allocation in its own REQUIRES_NEW transaction, while holding a `synchronized` lock that prevents concurrent threads from starting their MERGE before the first thread's REQUIRES_NEW has committed.**

The critical insight: the `synchronized` lock must be held in a non-transactional wrapper, which calls a SEPARATE CDI bean's `@Transactional(REQUIRES_NEW)` method. When that method returns, the CDI `@Transactional` interceptor commits the REQUIRES_NEW immediately (inside the `proceed()` call). The lock is still held at that point — T2 cannot acquire it until T1's commit is visible.

**Wrong pattern** — lock-inside-same-bean or synchronized-on-method:

```java
// ❌ CDI proxy commits AFTER method body returns (after synchronized releases)
@Transactional(REQUIRES_NEW)
public synchronized LedgerEntry save(...) {
    em.createNativeQuery(MERGE_SQL).executeUpdate();
    em.flush();
    // ... select next_seq
    em.persist(entry);
    return entry;
} // synchronized releases HERE; CDI interceptor commits AFTER HERE → race window exists
```

T2 can acquire the lock after the method body returns but before the CDI interceptor commits T1's REQUIRES_NEW. T2's MERGE still sees NOT MATCHED.

**Correct pattern** — separate CDI bean for the REQUIRES_NEW:

```java
// CDI bean A (caller, synchronized but NOT @Transactional)
@ApplicationScoped
class QhorusLedgerEntryRepository {
    @Inject QhorusSequenceAllocator sequenceAllocator; // separate bean!

@Override
    public synchronized LedgerEntry save(LedgerEntry entry, String tenancyId) {
        // sequenceAllocator.nextSequenceNumber() is a @Transactional(REQUIRES_NEW) call
        // through the CDI proxy. When it RETURNS, the REQUIRES_NEW is committed.
        // The synchronized lock is still held at that point — T2 is blocked.
        entry.sequenceNumber = sequenceAllocator.nextSequenceNumber(entry.subjectId);
        em.persist(entry);
        return entry;
    }
}

// CDI bean B (allocator — separate class so @Transactional applies via CDI proxy)
@ApplicationScoped
class QhorusSequenceAllocator {
    @Inject @LedgerPersistenceUnit EntityManager em;

@Transactional(TxType.REQUIRES_NEW)
    int nextSequenceNumber(UUID subjectId) {
        em.createNativeQuery(MERGE_SQL).setParameter(1, subjectId).executeUpdate();
        em.flush(); // required: AUTO flush mode doesn't flush before native queries
        Number n = (Number) em.createNativeQuery(SELECT_SQL)
            .setParameter(1, subjectId).getSingleResult();
        return n.intValue();
    } // CDI interceptor commits REQUIRES_NEW here — INSIDE the caller's synchronized block
}
```

T1 and T2 concurrent flow:
1. T1 acquires `synchronized(this)` → calls `sequenceAllocator.nextSequenceNumber()` → REQUIRES_NEW starts, MERGE INSERTs (subject_id, 2), REQUIRES_NEW COMMITS, method returns → lock still held
2. T2 tries to acquire `synchronized(this)` → blocked
3. T1 releases lock (save() body returns)
4. T2 acquires lock → calls `sequenceAllocator.nextSequenceNumber()` → MERGE sees MATCHED (T1's row committed) → UPDATEs next_seq to 3, REQUIRES_NEW COMMITS, returns 2

No PK violation.

### Why this is non-obvious

The naive fix — adding `@Transactional(REQUIRES_NEW)` to the `save()` method AND marking it `synchronized` — doesn't work. The CDI `@Transactional` interceptor commits the REQUIRES_NEW AFTER the method body returns. `synchronized` is released when the method body returns. There is a race window between "method body returns" (lock released) and "CDI interceptor commits" (REQUIRES_NEW visible). T2 can enter this window.

The fix requires understanding that CDI `@Transactional` is implemented as an `around` interceptor: `begin tx → proceed() [calls method body] → commit tx`. The commit happens in the interceptor, NOT inside the method body. Only by calling a SEPARATE CDI bean's REQUIRES_NEW method — where the commit happens inside `proceed()`, while the caller still holds the synchronized lock — is the race window eliminated.

PostgreSQL avoids this pattern entirely: its MERGE acquires a row-level lock before INSERT, serializing concurrent NOT MATCHED evaluations. H2 does not.

### Alternatives considered

QuarkusTestResourceLifecycleManager.start() silently ignores build-time fixed properties

### Symptom

`QuarkusTestResourceLifecycleManager.start()` returns a map containing a build-time fixed property (e.g. `quarkus.flyway.locations`). Quarkus logs a warning:

```
quarkus.flyway.locations is set to 'classpath:db/work/migration' but it is build time
fixed to 'db/migration'. Did you change the property after building the application?
```

The test proceeds with the build-time value. The override is silently discarded.

### Context

Occurs when a `@QuarkusTestResource` tries to configure a Flyway migration path, datasource, or any other property marked as build-time fixed in Quarkus. The `start()` method runs **after** augmentation (at runtime startup), so build-time properties are already baked in and cannot be changed.

### Root cause

Quarkus separates configuration into build-time and runtime phases. Build-time properties are resolved during augmentation, before any test infrastructure starts. `QuarkusTestResourceLifecycleManager.start()` executes at runtime — too late to influence augmentation output.

### Fix

Set build-time fixed properties in `src/test/resources/application.properties`, which is read during augmentation:

```properties
# Correct — read at augmentation time
quarkus.flyway.locations=classpath:db/work/migration,classpath:db/ledger/migration
```

Do **not** return build-time properties from `start()`. Reserve `start()` for runtime-only properties (JDBC URLs, usernames, ports) that the test container provides dynamically.

### Alternative — QuarkusTestProfile.getConfigOverrides() for per-profile build-time overrides

When different test classes need different build-time values (e.g. H2 for fast tests, PostgreSQL for integration tests), `application.properties` can't express this — it's one static file. Use `QuarkusTestProfile.getConfigOverrides()` instead: Quarkus triggers **re-augmentation** when a profile returns different build-time config, so each profile class gets its own augmentation with the correct value baked in.

```java
public abstract class PostgreSQLTestProfile implements QuarkusTestProfile {
    // db-kind is BUILD_TIME — getConfigOverrides() triggers re-augmentation
    @Override
    public Map<String, String> getConfigOverrides() {
        return Map.of("quarkus.datasource.db-kind", "postgresql");
    }

@Override
    public List<TestResourceEntry> testResources() {
        // Runtime properties (JDBC URL, credentials) stay in the test resource
        return List.of(new TestResourceEntry(PostgreSQLTestResource.class));
    }
}
```

**The split:** build-time properties (`db-kind`) in `getConfigOverrides()` (participates in augmentation); runtime properties (JDBC URL, credentials) in the test resource `start()` (applied after augmentation — fine for runtime config).

### Why this is non-obvious

The warning message is easy to miss in verbose test output. There is no error — the test starts normally with the wrong configuration. The symptom (missing tables, schema errors) appears later and points away from the config override as the cause.

**See also:** [GE-20260429-ede58e](GE-20260429-ede58e.md) — quarkus.flyway.migrate-at-start is build-time fixed — cannot be overridden | [GE-20260529-7985ba](GE-20260529-7985ba.md) — quarkus.flyway.migrate-at-start defaults to false in @QuarkusTest

Panache.withTransaction() uses the default persistence unit — silently wrong in apps with only a named PU

## Symptom

`IllegalStateException: No current Mutiny.Session` or `org.hibernate.SessionException` when a reactive service method is called from within a consumer app that has only a named datasource configured (no default datasource). The service works in the library's own tests (which configure a default datasource) but fails in the consumer.

## Context

A library's reactive service uses `Panache.withTransaction(() -> { ... })` (the static, zero-argument form). The consuming app configures a named datasource only:

```properties
# Consumer app — named datasource only, no default
quarkus.datasource.qhorus.db-kind=h2
quarkus.datasource.qhorus.reactive.url=...
```

The library tests configure a default datasource and pass. Consumer integration fails.

## Root cause

`Panache.withTransaction(Supplier<Uni<T>>)` (zero-argument form) always uses the **default** persistence unit. When a consumer app has no default PU, Panache cannot acquire a session and throws at runtime. The library's own tests define a default datasource (usually H2 in test config), so the problem is invisible until a consumer app is built.

## Fix

Use the named-PU overload `Panache.withTransaction(String persistenceUnitName, Supplier<Uni<T>>)`:

```java
// Before — uses default PU, breaks in consumers with named-PU-only config
return Panache.withTransaction(() -> {
    return messageStore.put(message);
});

// After — explicitly targets the named PU
return Panache.withTransaction("qhorus", () -> {
    return messageStore.put(message);
});
```

Apply consistently to all transactional methods in the library — if one method uses the named form and another uses the default form, intermittent failures result depending on which code path the consumer exercises first.

## Why this is non-obvious

The zero-argument `withTransaction()` is the documented primary form. The named-PU overload is not prominently documented. The failure only appears in consumers that don't configure a default datasource — the library's own tests pass, giving false confidence. The `IllegalStateException` message ("No current Mutiny.Session") doesn't mention the PU name mismatch.

