CDI container wiring vs service-loader wiring in large JVM frameworks

## Pattern

Large JVM frameworks that expose extension points make a foundational choice: wire extensions via **CDI container injection** or via **service-loader / explicit registration**. Both achieve the same structural depth (thousands of interfaces, deep abstraction hierarchies) but differ radically in how dependencies flow at runtime.

### CDI container wiring (Quarkus style)

Extensions are beans. Callers inject them via `@Inject`, `Instance<T>`, or `@Any Instance<T>`. The CDI container owns lifetime and resolution.

```java
// Extension point
public interface ExpiryPolicy {
    String name();
    boolean isExpired(Session s, Duration timeout);
}

// Discovery — zero explicit registration
@ApplicationScoped
public class PolicyRegistry {
    @Inject @Any Instance<ExpiryPolicy> policies;

public ExpiryPolicy get(String name) {
        return policies.stream()
            .filter(p -> p.name().equals(name))
            .findFirst().orElseThrow();
    }
}
```

### Service-loader wiring (Hibernate style)

Extensions are registered via `META-INF/services/<InterfaceFQN>` files or explicit `ServiceRegistry` calls. The framework owns resolution; no CDI container required.

```java
// META-INF/services/org.hibernate.integrator.spi.Integrator
// → com.example.MyIntegrator

// Discovery — explicit service lookup
ServiceLoader<Integrator> loader =
    ServiceLoader.load(Integrator.class, classLoader);
```

## Why this is non-obvious

The two approaches look structurally identical at a coarse level — same number of interfaces, same abstraction depth ratio. A structural fingerprint alone won't distinguish them. The signal is in the **injection-to-file ratio**: CDI-wired frameworks approach 0.4 injections/file; service-loader frameworks stay near 0.002. That gap (200×) survives normalisation and is the discriminator.

This matters when **integrating the two styles**: a Hibernate extension brought into a Quarkus application must be wrapped in a CDI producer or adapter bean — the wiring strategies don't compose directly.

### Alternatives considered

- **Manual factory / registry**: explicit `Map<String, Extension>` maintained in code. Works, but requires every extension author to register manually. Fragile at scale.
- **Reflection-based scanning**: scan classpath for implementations. Non-deterministic ordering, classloading hazards, slow startup.
- **Both at once (hybrid)**: use service-loader for bootstrap discovery, CDI for runtime injection. Adds complexity; only warranted when a framework must work both inside and outside a CDI container.

Canonical CloudEvent adapter pattern — 7 rules for CDI async adapters

Seven rules every CloudEvent adapter in the platform must satisfy.
Discovered during casehubio/connectors#20 — two existing adapters (IoT, Qhorus)
had 2 bugs, 1 silent failure path, and 1 pattern inconsistency. All fixed together.

### The pattern

| Rule | Requirement | Failure mode |
|------|-------------|-------------|
| ObjectMapper | Injected — never a private static instance | Static instance isolates serialisation config from app's shared mapper; custom serializers invisible |
| tenancyId | Null-safe — extension omitted when null | SDK serialises null extension as literal `"null"` or throws NPE |
| fireAsync | Always `.exceptionally(ex -> { LOG.warn(...); return null; })` | Unhandled `CompletionStage` swallows downstream observer failures silently |
| Serialisation error | Catch at WARN, fire with `new byte[0]` — never throw | Unchecked exception from `@ObservesAsync` propagates into CDI managed executor and is silently swallowed |
| type derivation | From a stable semantic field on the event record | Instance IDs are mutable; CloudEvent `type` is used for routing rules that must be stable |
| Severity | WARN for degraded paths | SEVERE causes alert fatigue; serialisation failure is degraded, not catastrophic |
| datacontenttype | Set `application/json` when data is ObjectMapper-serialised | Consumers cannot parse the `data` field without knowing its format; omitting it forces guessing |

`tenancyId` always sourced from the event record — never from `CurrentPrincipal`,
which is `@RequestScoped` and inactive in `@ObservesAsync` observers.

### Why this is non-obvious

Rules 3 and 4 interact: `fireAsync()` returns a `CompletionStage` that swallows
failures silently, but a thrown exception from the observer method *also* vanishes
into CDI's managed executor. Most developers add `.exceptionally()` (rule 3) but
don't realise that a throw *before* `fireAsync` is called (rule 4 — serialisation
error) is equally invisible. The error paths are different but the symptom is identical:
the event silently disappears with no log entry.

### Why this fix

The alternative — letting exceptions propagate — appears correct because CDI
"should" handle observer exceptions. But `@ObservesAsync` runs on a managed
executor thread where exceptions propagate into a `CompletionStage` that nobody
awaits. The pattern of catch-log-continue is the only way to make failures visible.

### Fix

Reference implementations:
- `QhorusCloudEventAdapter` (casehub-qhorus)
- `ConnectorsCloudEventAdapter` (casehub-connectors)
- `IoTCloudEventAdapter` (casehub-iot)

```java
@ApplicationScoped
public class ExampleCloudEventAdapter {

private static final Logger LOG = Logger.getLogger(ExampleCloudEventAdapter.class);

private final Event<CloudEvent> cloudEventBus;
    private final ObjectMapper objectMapper;  // rule 1: injected

@Inject
    public ExampleCloudEventAdapter(Event<CloudEvent> cloudEventBus, ObjectMapper objectMapper) {
        this.cloudEventBus = cloudEventBus;
        this.objectMapper = objectMapper;
    }

public void onEvent(@ObservesAsync SomeDomainEvent event) {
        byte[] data;
        try {
            data = objectMapper.writeValueAsBytes(event);
        } catch (JsonProcessingException e) {
            LOG.warnf("Serialisation failed: %s", e.getMessage());  // rule 4 + 6
            data = new byte[0];
        }

CloudEventBuilder builder = CloudEventBuilder.v1()
                .withId(UUID.randomUUID().toString())
                .withType("io.casehub.domain." + event.semanticType())  // rule 5
                .withSource(URI.create("/source"))
                .withTime(event.occurredAt().atOffset(ZoneOffset.UTC))
                .withDataContentType("application/json")
                .withData(data);

if (event.tenancyId() != null) {  // rule 2
            builder = builder.withExtension("tenancyid", event.tenancyId());
        }

cloudEventBus.fireAsync(builder.build())
                .exceptionally(ex -> {  // rule 3 + 6
                    LOG.warnf(ex, "CloudEvent dispatch failed");
                    return null;
                });
    }
}
```

### ⚠️ Rule 3 exception — reactive messaging ack chains

Rule 3 (`.exceptionally()`) **must NOT be applied** when the `CompletionStage` is
chained to a message acknowledgement, as in SmallRye Reactive Messaging `@Incoming`
consumers:

```java
// WRONG — .exceptionally() swallows the exception; message.ack() always runs → silent data loss
return cloudEventBus.fireAsync(ce)
    .exceptionally(ex -> { LOG.warnf(ex, "dispatch failed"); return null; })
    .thenCompose(ignored -> message.ack());

// CORRECT — .whenComplete() preserves the exception; thenCompose skips on failure → SmallRye nacks
return cloudEventBus.fireAsync(ce)
    .whenComplete((v, t) -> { if (t != null) LOG.warnf(t, "dispatch failed"); })
    .thenCompose(ignored -> message.ack());
```

With `.exceptionally()`: exception swallowed → `null` returned → `thenCompose` fires →
`message.ack()` runs → message permanently consumed regardless of dispatch outcome.

With `.whenComplete()`: exception preserved on the stage → `thenCompose` skips its lambda
→ exception surfaces to SmallRye → message nacked → retried or dead-lettered.

Rule 3 applies **only in pure fire-and-forget dispatch** (the `CompletionStage` is not
returned or chained further). CDI `@ObservesAsync` adapters are always fire-and-forget.
SmallRye `@Incoming` consumers return the stage for ack/nack signalling — they are not.

### Alternatives considered

Hardcoding a consumer-specific @PersistenceUnit in a generic Quarkus extension silently breaks all other consumers

## Symptom

A subagent fixed `"Unsatisfied dependency for type EntityManager and qualifiers [@Default]"` in a consuming application (Claudony) by adding `@PersistenceUnit("qhorus")` to all `EntityManager` injection points in a generic extension's runtime beans. The error disappeared in Claudony. Every other consumer of the extension then failed with the mirror error: `"Unsatisfied dependency for type EntityManager and qualifiers [@PersistenceUnit("qhorus")]"`.

## Context

Occurs when a Quarkus application configures only a named datasource/persistence unit with no default. CDI then provides only a `@PersistenceUnit("name")` qualified `EntityManager` — the `@Default` qualified one is absent. An extension injecting bare `EntityManager` fails. The tempting fix is to add the named qualifier to the extension's beans.

## Root cause

The fix confuses the symptom (missing `@Default` EntityManager) with the root cause (the extension has no mechanism to select which persistence unit to use — it always assumed the default). Adding a consumer-specific qualifier to a reusable extension is an architectural error: it hard-couples the extension to one consumer's datasource configuration.

## Fix

Add a configurable persistence unit name to the extension's config (e.g. `quarkus.ledger.datasource`, empty = default), a custom CDI qualifier (`@LedgerPersistenceUnit`), and a producer that selects the right `EntityManager` at startup:

```java
@ApplicationScoped
public class LedgerEntityManagerProducer {
    @Inject LedgerConfig config;

@Produces @LedgerPersistenceUnit
    public EntityManager produce(@Any Instance<EntityManager> instance) {
        String pu = config.datasource().orElse("").trim();
        if (pu.isBlank()) {
            return instance.select(Default.Literal.INSTANCE).get();
        }
        return instance.select(new PersistenceUnitLiteral(pu)).get();
    }
}
```

All extension beans inject `@LedgerPersistenceUnit EntityManager` instead of bare `EntityManager`. Consumers with only a named datasource set `quarkus.ledger.datasource=mydb`; all others need no config change.

## Why this is non-obvious

The error message names the qualifier (`[@Default]`) and the natural fix is to supply that qualifier — or supply the consumer's qualifier. It takes a step back to recognise that the qualifier itself is not the problem; the problem is the extension assuming a default datasource exists. The right fix adds a level of indirection (configurable producer) rather than patching the symptom.

### Why this fix

The qualifier + producer approach is IntelliJ-stable (real CDI annotation, not stripped as an unused import), portable (works with any datasource name), and testable (the producer is a plain CDI bean).

### Alternatives considered

- Annotating all 8 injection points with `@PersistenceUnit("qhorus")`: makes the extension unusable with casehub-engine, quarkus-workitems, or any non-Qhorus consumer
- Documenting "must have a default datasource": too restrictive — named-only datasource setups are valid and common in multi-tenant apps

**See also:** [GE-20260424-a02588](GE-20260424-a02588.md) — CDI @Qualifier + AnnotationLiteral producer is the correct fix for this architectural error

