emitOn(Infrastructure.getDefaultWorkerPool()) — correct way to shift blocking I/O off Vert.x IO thread in a reactive SPI

## Context

A reactive SPI method returns `Uni<T>` and needs to make a blocking call (e.g. HTTP to an embedding service, JDBC, file I/O). The SPI is called from a `@ConsumeEvent` handler (Vert.x event bus) which runs on the Vert.x IO thread unless `blocking = true` is set.

## Technique

Use `.emitOn(Infrastructure.getDefaultWorkerPool())` on the `Uni` **before** the blocking operation. This shifts the execution to the Mutiny default worker pool:

```java
@Override
public Uni<AgentAssignment> select(AgentRoutingContext context, List<AgentCandidate> candidates) {
    // Classify (in-memory, fast — can stay on caller thread)
    List<ClassifiedCandidate> classified = classifier.classify(candidates, ...);

return Uni.createFrom()
        .voidItem()
        .emitOn(Infrastructure.getDefaultWorkerPool())  // shift here, before blocking work
        .map(ignored -> {
            // Everything from here runs on the worker pool
            float[] queryVector = embeddingProvider.embed(queryText);  // blocking HTTP call
            // ... build scored candidates ...
            return TrustCandidateClassifier.decide(classified, scored, capability);
        });
}
```

## Why This Is Non-Obvious

Three common but wrong alternatives:

**1. `Uni.createFrom().item(() -> blockingOperation())`**
Executes the supplier on the thread that subscribes (the IO thread). Still blocks if called from a `@ConsumeEvent` handler.

**2. `@Blocking` on the handler method**
Moves the *entire* handler to a worker thread, including all in-memory work before the SPI call. Wasteful and scatters the threading decision into the caller rather than the SPI implementation.

**3. `Uni.createFrom().emitter(em -> { em.complete(blocking()); })`**
Also executes on the subscribing thread unless `.emitOn()` is chained.

The correct model: the `Uni` pipeline is lazy. `.emitOn(workerPool)` inserts a thread-handoff at that point in the pipeline — everything downstream of it executes on the worker pool when the `Uni` is subscribed. Place it immediately before the first blocking call, after any fast in-memory preparation.

## Constraints

Requires `io.smallrye.mutiny:mutiny` and `io.smallrye.mutiny.infrastructure.Infrastructure` on the classpath (shipped with Quarkus). `Infrastructure.getDefaultWorkerPool()` is the standard Mutiny executor for blocking work — do not pass a custom executor unless you need isolation.

**See also:** [GE-20260529-b994c2](GE-20260529-b994c2.md) — Uni.createFrom().item(supplier) with emitOn(): supplier still runs on subscription thread (use runSubscriptionOn instead)

@Alternative without @Priority silently disables @IfBuildProperty-gated beans — dependencies activate, service does not

## Symptom

CDI deployment failure or `UnsatisfiedResolutionException` in a consumer app. All injected dependencies of the gated service are activated, but the service itself is not injectable. Adding the class to `quarkus.arc.selected-alternatives` fixes it.

## Context

A Quarkus extension adds a service bean with both `@Alternative` and `@IfBuildProperty`:

```java
@Alternative
@IfBuildProperty(name = "casehub.qhorus.reactive.enabled", stringValue = "true")
@ApplicationScoped
public class QhorusDashboardService {
    @Inject ReactiveChannelService channelService; // ← this gets activated
    ...
}
```

The consumer app sets the build property, expects the bean to be injectable — and gets a deployment failure because `QhorusDashboardService` itself is not in the CDI context.

## Root cause

`@IfBuildProperty` controls whether the bean class is included in the CDI context at augmentation time. `@Alternative` controls whether an included bean is *selected* (active) — and without `@Priority`, it defaults to deselected unless listed in `quarkus.arc.selected-alternatives`.

These two mechanisms compose independently: `@IfBuildProperty` gates **inclusion**; `@Alternative` gates **selection**. A bean can be included (build property met) but still deselected (`@Alternative` without `@Priority`). When the bean is deselected, Arc does not inject it anywhere — but its own injected dependencies are still resolved at augmentation, causing the mismatch.

## Fix

Remove `@Alternative` entirely when there is no interface or superclass to override. `@IfBuildProperty` alone correctly controls activation:

```java
// Before — @Alternative forces manual selection
@Alternative
@IfBuildProperty(name = "casehub.qhorus.reactive.enabled", stringValue = "true")
@ApplicationScoped
public class QhorusDashboardService { ... }

// After — @IfBuildProperty handles activation; no manual selection needed
@IfBuildProperty(name = "casehub.qhorus.reactive.enabled", stringValue = "true")
@ApplicationScoped
public class QhorusDashboardService { ... }
```

If `@Alternative` is legitimately needed (the bean overrides another bean's type), add `@Priority(1)` to activate it globally — consistent with how Quarkus's own reactive alternatives work (e.g. `ReactiveChannelService`, `ReactiveMessageService` in casehub-qhorus).

## Why this is non-obvious

`@IfBuildProperty` looks like it fully controls the bean's lifecycle. The interaction with `@Alternative`'s deselection mechanism is not documented in Quarkus — you only discover it when the build property is set, the service's dependencies are all activated, but the service itself isn't injectable. The error message points to an unsatisfied dependency, not the `@Alternative` deselection.

